## **3. What Makes Great Crema?**

To understand why one blend might outperform the other, we must first understand the physics of crema. Crema is essentially an emulsion formed by air bubbles combining with the soluble oils in ground coffee. It is created when water under high pressure (usually 9 bars) forces carbon dioxide (CO2) out of the beans.

Three main factors influence crema production:

1. **The Presence of Robusta Beans:** Robusta beans contain almost double the caffeine and significantly less lipid (fat) content than Arabica, but they produce far more CO2 and structure. This creates a thicker, more stable foam.
1. **Freshness:** Freshly roasted beans contain more CO2. As beans age, they degas, leading to thin or non-existent crema.
1. **Processing Method:** "Natural" or dry-processed beans often retain more oils and body compared to washed beans, aiding in crema formation.

## **4. Lavazza Super Crema: Deep Dive**

### **Bean Composition & Origin**

As the name implies, Lavazza Super Crema is engineered specifically for texture. It is a blend of washed Brazilian Arabica beans, Indian Arabica, and—crucially—high-quality Robusta beans from Indonesia and Vietnam. The ratio stands roughly at 60% Arabica and 40% Robusta.

### **Roast Profile**

Super Crema features a medium-dark roast. It is dark enough to lower the acidity but not so oily that it clogs super-automatic espresso machines. This balance is often referred to as an "espresso roast."

### **Crema Characteristics**

This blend lives up to its name. The inclusion of 40% Robusta acts as a structural scaffold for the foam. When extracted properly, Super Crema produces a thick, hazelnut-colored layer that can withstand the "sugar test" (where a sprinkle of sugar rests on the foam for a few seconds before sinking). It is resilient and persistent.

### **Flavor Profile**

Expect notes of roasted hazelnut and brown sugar. It has a very low acidity and a heavy body. It is designed to punch through milk, making it a favorite for lattes and cappuccinos.

